<image 1> What could be the reason for the corky outgrowths on a young ash tree by the roadside in Littondale, Yorkshire?

A. Fungal disease
B. Bacterial disease
C. Don't know or not sure
D. Genetic abnormality
E. Insect feeding

The corky outgrowths on the young ash tree in the image are likely caused by:

E. Insect feeding

These outgrowths are characteristic of damage caused by the Emerald Ash Borer (Agrilus planipennis), an invasive beetle that feeds on ash trees. The larvae of this insect bore into the bark and cambium layer of the tree, disrupting the flow of nutrients and water, which can lead to the formation of these corky outgrowths as the tree attempts to heal the damage. This is a common sign of infestation by the Emerald Ash Borer.
